{"title_page": "Peter Vilho", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =Rear Admiral\n|name             = Peter Vilho\n|president        = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start       = March 21, 2020\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Penda Ya Ndakolo]]\n|successor        = \n|birth_date       = 02 February 1962\n|birth_place      = [[Windhoek]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|nationality = Namibian\n|party            = \n|spouse           = \n|children         = \n|allegiance       = {{NAM}}\n|battles = \n|branch        = PLAN</br>Namibian Army</br>Namibian Navy\n|serviceyears  = 1983-2017\n|rank          = [[Rear Admiral]]\n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*Excellent Order of the Eagle, third Class\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Rear Admiral]] '''Peter Hafeni  Vilho''' (born 02 February 1962) is a Namibian politician and retired military officer who is currently a member of Parliament and the Minister of Defence, he has served as the Commander of the [[Namibian Navy]]. He was appointed the Commander of the maritime wing of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] in 2002. In September 2017 he was appointed as Executive Director of the Ministry of Defence. In March 2020, Namibian president Hage Geingob appointed Vilho as the Minister of Defense and Veteran Affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://informante.web.na/central-bank-governor-appointed-finance-minister/|title=Central bank Governor appointed finance minister|last=Terblanch\u00e9|first=Ni\u00ebl|date=2020-03-22|website=Informant\u00e9|language=en-ZA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===PLAN ===\nIn 1983 Vilho was an Engineering Instructor at the Tobias Hainyeko Training Centre, Lubango, Angola. In 1984 he was appointed as an Engineer Company Commander and Anti-tank Battery Commander at the Northern Front and Striking Unit.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref>\n\n===NDF===\nRear Admiral Vilho's career in the Namibian Defence Force started in 1990 after Namibia's independence when he was inducted with the rank of [[Captain]] and appointed as paymaster for the 125 Battalion. In 1993, he was promoted to the rank of Major and appointed as the Chief paymaster for the Army Headquarters. Later in the year he was appointed Staff Officer grade2 (SO2) Operations and Training Army Headquarters with the same rank. Between the following year and 1998 he attended the Admiral Wandenkolk Instruction Centre' (CIAW) in Rio de Janeiro.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref> Upon graduating he was appointed as the Chief of Staff NDF Maritime Wing in 1998. In 2001 he was appointed as the Deputy Commander NDF Maritime Wing with rank of [[Commander]] and in the following year following the death of Captain (Navy) Phestus Sakaria the Commander NDF Maritime Wing Vilho was appointed as his successor with the rank of Naval Captain. The rank of Commodore was bestowed on him in 2004 at the commissioning of the Maritime Wing as a fully fledged Navy. In 2007 he ascended to the rank of Rear Admiral.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref> \n\n===Retiremment and Politics===\nHe retired from active service in September 2017 to be appointed as Executive Director of the Ministry of Defence and on the 21 March 2020 he was appointed as a non voting member of parliament by President [[Hage Geingob]] and as Minister of Defence succeeding [[Penda Ya Ndakolo|Penda ya Ndakolo]].\n\n===Qualifications===\n\n*1990- 1992 Finance Officer Advanced Course and Resource Management Course at Ford Benning, USA\n*1994 - Junior Staff and Command Course, Namibia\n*1995 - 1998 Naval Officers Formation Course, Brazil\n*2005 - Advanced Course on Politics and Strategy at the National War College, Brazil\n*2007 - Master of Business Administration from Maastricht School of Management Netherlands\n\n===Military Decorations===\n*Order of the Eagle 3rd Class \u2013 Government of the Republic of Namibia<ref>{{Cite news\n|title=Namibians honoured by President\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date= 28 August 2014\n|url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>\n*Commendation Medal 1st Class \u2013 Namibian Defence Force\n*Ten Year Service Medal \u2013 Namibian Defence Force\n*Southern Cross Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Navy Pioneers Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Navy Cross Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Gold Star Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Sacharia Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Achievement Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Ten Year Service \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*750 Days  at Sea Service Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n* [[File:Order of Naval Merit - Grand Officer (Brazil) - ribbon bar.png|x20px]] [[Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)|Order of Naval Merit (Grand Officer) Medal \u2013 Brazilian Navy]]\n*Medal of Merit \u201cTamandare\u201d \u2013 Brazilian Navy\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Vacant\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Namibian Navy]] Commander\n| years = 2004{{snd}}2017\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Sinsy Nghipandua]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vilho, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix =Rear Admiral\n|name             = Peter Vilho\n|president        = [[Hage Geingob]]\n|term_start       = March 21, 2020\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Penda Ya Ndakolo]]\n|successor        = \n|birth_date       = 02 February 1962\n|birth_place      = [[Windhoek]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|nationality = Namibian\n|party            = \n|spouse           = \n|children         = \n|allegiance       = {{NAM}}\n|battles = \n|branch        = Namibian Navy\n|serviceyears  = 1990-2017\n|rank          = [[Rear Admiral]]\n| awards        = {{plainlist |\n*Excellent Order of the Eagle, third Class\n}}\n}}\n\n[[Rear Admiral]] '''Peter Hafeni  Vilho''' (born 02 February 1962) is a Namibian politician and retired military officer who is currently a member of Parliament and the Minister of Defence, he has served as the Commander of the [[Namibian Navy]]. He was appointed the Commander of the maritime wing of the [[Namibian Defence Force]] in 2002. In September 2017 he was appointed as Executive Director of the Ministry of Defence. In March 2020, Namibian president Hage Geingob appointed Vilho as the Minister of Defense and Veteran Affairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://informante.web.na/central-bank-governor-appointed-finance-minister/|title=Central bank Governor appointed finance minister|last=Terblanch\u00e9|first=Ni\u00ebl|date=2020-03-22|website=Informant\u00e9|language=en-ZA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===PLAN ===\nIn 1983 Vilho was an Engineering Instructor at the Tobias Hainyeko Training Centre, Lubango, Angola. In 1984 he was appointed as an Engineer Company Commander and Anti-tank Battery Commander at the Northern Front and Striking Unit.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref>\n\n===NDF===\nRear Admiral Vilho's career in the Namibian Defence Force started in 1990 after Namibia's independence when he was inducted with the rank of [[Captain]] and appointed as paymaster for the 125 Battalion. In 1993, he was promoted to the rank of Major and appointed as the Chief paymaster for the Army Headquarters. Later in the year he was appointed Staff Officer grade2 (SO2) Operations and Training Army Headquarters with the same rank. Between the following year and 1998 he attended the Admiral Wandenkolk Instruction Centre' (CIAW) in Rio de Janeiro.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref> Upon graduating he was appointed as the Chief of Staff NDF Maritime Wing in 1998. In 2001 he was appointed as the Deputy Commander NDF Maritime Wing with rank of [[Commander]] and in the following year following the death of Captain (Navy) Phestus Sakaria the Commander NDF Maritime Wing Vilho was appointed as his successor with the rank of Naval Captain. The rank of Commodore was bestowed on him in 2004 at the commissioning of the Maritime Wing as a fully fledged Navy. In 2007 he ascended to the rank of Rear Admiral.<ref>http://www.mod.gov.na/permanent-secretary</ref> \n\n===Retiremment and Politics===\nHe retired from active service in September 2017 to be appointed as Executive Director of the Ministry of Defence and on the 21 March 2020 he was appointed as a non voting member of parliament by President [[Hage Geingob]] and as Minister of Defence succeeding [[Penda Ya Ndakolo|Penda ya Ndakolo]].\n\n===Qualifications===\n\n*1990- 1992 Finance Officer Advanced Course and Resource Management Course at Ford Benning, USA\n*1994 - Junior Staff and Command Course, Namibia\n*1995 - 1998 Naval Officers Formation Course, Brazil\n*2005 - Advanced Course on Politics and Strategy at the National War College, Brazil\n*2007 - Master of Business Administration from Maastricht School of Management Netherlands\n\n===Military Decorations===\n*Order of the Eagle 3rd Class \u2013 Government of the Republic of Namibia<ref>{{Cite news\n|title=Namibians honoured by President\n|newspaper=[[New Era (Namibia)|New Era]]\n|date= 28 August 2014\n|url=http://www.newera.com.na/2014/08/28/namibians-honoured-by-president/}}</ref>\n*Commendation Medal 1st Class \u2013 Namibian Defence Force\n*Ten Year Service Medal \u2013 Namibian Defence Force\n*Southern Cross Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Navy Pioneers Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Navy Cross Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Gold Star Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Sacharia Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Achievement Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*Ten Year Service \u2013 Namibian Navy\n*750 Days  at Sea Service Medal \u2013 Namibian Navy\n* [[File:Order of Naval Merit - Grand Officer (Brazil) - ribbon bar.png|x20px]] [[Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)|Order of Naval Merit (Grand Officer) Medal \u2013 Brazilian Navy]]\n*Medal of Merit \u201cTamandare\u201d \u2013 Brazilian Navy\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef\n| before = Vacant\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title = [[Namibian Navy]] Commander\n| years = 2004{{snd}}2017\n}}\n{{s-aft\n| after = [[Sinsy Nghipandua]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vilho, Peter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Namibian military personnel]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Naval Merit (Brazil)]]\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Vilho"}
{"title_page": "Bupa", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = Bupa\n| logo     = Bupa logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type     = [[Company limited by guarantee]]\n| location         = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1947}}\n| key_people       = [[Evelyn Bourke]], CEO<br>Roger Davis, Chairman\n| industry         = [[Healthcare]], [[Insurance]]\n| products         = [[health insurance]], care homes, health at work services, hospitals, dental clinics, health assessments\n| revenue          = {{profit}} \u00a311.9 billion [[Pound sterling|GBP]] (2018)\n| operating_income = {{profit}} \u00a3613 million [[Pound sterling|GBP]] (2018)\n| num_employees    = 80,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{url|http://www.bupa.com}}\n}}\n'''Bupa''' {{IPAc-en|b|u\u02d0|p|\u0259}} is a British international [[healthcare]] provisioning and multi-[[insurance]] group, with its origins and headquarters in the United Kingdom, but now serving 32 million customers in 190 countries. It is a private healthcare [[company limited by guarantee]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Financial results |url=https://www.bupa.com/corporate/our-performance/financial-results |website=Bupa |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref> unlike the UK's [[National Health Service]] (NHS), which is a [[tax-funded healthcare]] system. While initially growing organically through [[Greenfield project|green-field]] expansions, it has recently tended to function akin to a [[Private Equity]] firm, with its corporate strategy heavily influenced by [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] activity in order to consolidate itself as a market leader in healthcare provisioning and multi-insurance. It is consistently ranked among the best places to work, having placed 5th in the 2019 edition of [[LinkedIn]]'s Top Companies in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carroll |first=Katie |date=3 April 2019 |title=Top Companies 2019: Where the UK wants to work now |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/top-companies-2019-where-uk-wants-work-now-katie-carroll/ |website=LinkedIn |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBupa (originally the '''British United Provident Association''') was established in 1947<ref name=\"Health Dialog sold 2007\"/> when seventeen British [[provident association]]s joined together to provide healthcare for the general public. The firm is a [[private company limited by guarantee]]; it has no [[shareholder]]s, and any [[profit (accounting)|profit]]s (after [[tax]]) are reinvested in the business. The service offered by Bupa began as private medical insurance, offering policies to individuals, companies and other organisations, and eventually expanded to include privately run Bupa hospitals.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Acquisitions and Divestments===\n\nIn 2007, the company announced the sale of its UK hospitals to [[Spire Healthcare]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kollewe |first=Julia |date=18 June 2007 |title=BUPA sells hospitals to private equity firm |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/jun/18/privateequity1 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> However, during 2008, the firm acquired the [[London]]-based [[Cromwell Hospital]] flagship hospital to provide healthcare to its members and other private patients including [[medical tourism|medical tourists]] from outside the UK.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nApproval was given in the same year for a merger between Bupa's Australian arm (which until then comprised HBA and Mutual Community) and insurance group MBF.<ref>{{cite web |title=MBF-BUPA merger gets court go ahead |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/05/14/2244271.htm |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=14 May 2008}}</ref> The merger created what is now Australia's largest private health insurance group, with 3.98m lives covered. On 1 December 2008, Clinovia's name was changed to '''Bupa Home Healthcare'''.  In October 2010 the firm sold Bupa Health Assurance to [[Resolution Limited]], and it has been rebranded as part of Friends Life.<ref>[http://www.ftadviser.com/FinancialAdviser/Insurance/HealthcareAndProtection/News/article/20101021/fcd4bb60-d849-11df-a180-00144f2af8e8/Bupa-insurance-operation-snapped-up-by-Resolution.jsp Bupa insurance operation snapped up by Resolution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024215648/http://www.ftadviser.com/FinancialAdviser/Insurance/HealthcareAndProtection/News/article/20101021/fcd4bb60-d849-11df-a180-00144f2af8e8/Bupa-insurance-operation-snapped-up-by-Resolution.jsp |date=24 October 2010 }} - Financial Times</ref> At the end of 2012 Bupa acquired the largest private healthcare network in [[Poland]], Lux Med, from the [[private equity]] fund [[Mid Europa Partners]] for \u20ac400m.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mid Europa Completes the Sale of LUX MED to Bupa |url=http://www.mideuropa.com/media/news/2013/mid-europa-completes-the-sale-of-lux-med-to-bupa/ |publisher=Mid Europa Partners |date=15 April 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> In February 2015 Bupa acquired a controlling share in Chilean private healthcare network Cruz Blanca, which has a 21% share in the local market.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grupo ingl\u00e9s Bupa Sanitas negocia compra de Cruz Blanca y pagar\u00e1 alto premio por acci\u00f3n |trans-title=English group Bupa Sanitas negotiates purchase of Cruz Blanca and will pay high premium per share |url=http://www.lasegunda.com/Noticias/Economia/2013/12/897015/grupo-ingles-negocia-compra-de-cruz-blanca-y-pagara-alto-premio-por-accion |newspaper=[[La Segunda]] |language=Spanish |date=2 December 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> It emerged in January 2016 that the company was to sell its domiciliary care business, which provided care to around 35,500 people, to [[Celesio]] AG.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celesio in exclusivity to acquire Bupa\u2019s home care division|url=http://healthinvestor.co.uk/ShowArticle.aspx?ID=4582|accessdate=27 January 2016|publisher=Health Investor|date=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, it has diversified away from its core health insurance business and is now an international healthcare company with services that include [[travel insurance]], [[health insurance]], [[care home]]s, [[expatriate insurance]], [[health assessments]], [[occupational health]] services and hospitals. When the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]] came into force in April 2013 Bupa won the first high-value contract \u2013 a \u00a3235m deal to provide musculoskeletal services in West Sussex jointly with [[Central Surrey Health]] in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Denis |date=19 November 2014 |title=Private firms on course to net \u00a39bn of NHS contracts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/nov/19/private-firms-nhs-contracts-circle-healthcare-bupa-virgin-care-care-uk |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt bought the dentistry chain Oasis in November 2016 for \u00a3835 million from [[private equity]] firm [[Bridgepoint Capital]].  Oasis runs 380 UK dental practices, both NHS and private, with more than 1,800 dentists. It has an annual revenue of \u00a3277 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bupa snaps up dentistry group Oasis for \u00a3835m from private equity house Bridgepoint|url=http://www.cityam.com/253915/bupa-snaps-up-dentistry-group-oasis-835m-private-equity|accessdate=15 December 2016|newspaper=[[City AM]]|date=18 November 2016}}</ref> The name of the business was changed to Bupa Dental Care. In January 2019 it acquired 9 more practices, making a total of 23 in 6 months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bupa acquires nine new UK and Ireland dental practices |url=https://www.dentistry.co.uk/2019/01/23/bupa-acquires-nine-new-uk-ireland-dental-practices/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 |publisher=Dentistry |date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt bought two care homes in [[Poole]] from Primetower in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bupa UK acquires The Links and The Lindsay care homes in Poole|url=http://www.primetower.com/care.htm|accessdate=24 December 2016|publisher=Primetower}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 it sold 122 care homes, with 9,000 beds, to [[HC-One]] for \u00a3300 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bow |first=Michael |date=23 August 2017 |title=HC-One seals Bupa \u00a3300m care home deal despite frets on debt |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/hcone-seals-bupa-300m-care-home-deal-despite-frets-on-debt-a3618196.html |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018-19 financial year, Bupa remained the biggest player by customer numbers, with almost 3.6 million customers. However, the insurer has experienced losses in Australia- 50,000 net customer losses across all products and almost 80,000 of its core hospital cover customers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/financial-services/bupa-biggest-loser-in-private-health-exodus-20191105-p537l3|title=Bupa biggest loser in private health exodus|last=Fernyhough|first=James|date=2019-11-05|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nThe company has its head office in central [[London]], with main UK contact centres in [[Staines]] and [[Salford Quays]]. There are also offices in [[Brighton]] (Bupa Global), [[Bristol]] (Bupa Dental Care) and [[Leeds]] (Bupa Care Services) in the UK, [[Adelaide]], [[Brisbane]], [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]] in Australia (Bupa Australia and Bupa Aged Care Australia), Chile (Bupa Chile), New Delhi (Max Bupa), Madrid (Sanitas), Boston ([[Health Dialog]]), Beijing (Bupa China), Hong Kong (Bupa Hong Kong & Quality Healthcare), Jeddah ([[Bupa Arabia]]), and Miami,{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n[[File:Sede de Sanitas (Madrid) 02.jpg|240px|thumbnail|Bupa (''Sanitas'') offices in [[Madrid]] ([[Spain]]).]]\nThe firm also owns several healthcare companies overseas including Spain's largest healthcare company, Sanitas, and acquired ihi Danmark and Amedex (Miami, US) in September 2005. In December 2007, it purchased DCA Agedcare Group in Australia and New Zealand, making it a leading player in these markets. Also in December 2007, it announced the purchase of [[Health Dialog]],<ref name=\"Health Dialog sold 2007\">{{cite web |title=Health Dialog sold in $775M deal |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/stories/2007/12/17/daily26.html?jst=b_ln_hl |work=[[Boston Business Journal]] |date=18 December 2007 |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> a provider of chronic condition management and \"shared decision making\" services.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn April 2013, the company acquired Lux Med, Poland's largest private healthcare provider which runs businesses in health funding and provision all over the country through a national network of 194 health centres, including outpatient facilities, diagnostic centres, hospitals, and a large nursing and residential care home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bupa.com/corporate/bupa-where-you-are/poland|title=Bupa in Poland|last=bupa.com|first=Bupa Corporate Website|date=17 July 2017|website=Bupa Corporate Website}}</ref>\n\nThe firm has entered the Indian health insurance market through a joint venture with the local conglomerate, [[Max Healthcare|Max India]], called '''[[Max Bupa]] Health Insurance Limited'''.<ref>[http://www.maxindia.com/newsjuly11.html Max India Press Release New Delhi, 11 July 2008.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510133025/http://www.maxindia.com/newsjuly11.html |date=10 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn the Middle East, Bupa has entered into a joint-venture partnership with Nazer Group \u2013 a family-owned diversified holding company \u2013 and created '''Bupa Middle East''' in 1997, operating out of [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc-bahrain.com/companies/2841/bupa-middle-east-ltd | title=Bupa Middle East Ltd | publisher=Northstar Media | work=Arabian Business Community (ABC) | accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> When health insurance regulation issues arose in Saudi Arabia, the company was floated on the Saudi stock market as '''Bupa Arabia''', which is currently the leading health insurance company in Saudi Arabia.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAccording to Stuart Fletcher in 2013 'there was a six percent decline in the number of individuals covered' by private health insurance, 'and the people who are more likely to claim are the least likely to drop the insurance, so the risk pool is deteriorating.' Bupa has protected its finances by reducing payments to consultants. This provoked the [[British Medical Association]] to complain to the [[Competition Commission]], which published a report into the private healthcare sector in 2013, probing insurers' power over consultants' fees. It decided that by trying to keep prices down and promote competition, Bupa was doing \"exactly what customers would expect\". But it did warn that companies like Bupa need to ensure they communicate better with policyholders about what their premiums entitle them to.<ref>{{cite news|title=CITY INTERVIEW: Boss Stuart Fletcher fighting the flab at Bupa|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-2532338/CITY-INTERVIEW-Boss-Stuart-Fletcher-fighting-flab-Bupa.html|accessdate=3 January 2014 |author=Sunderland, Ruth |newspaper=[[This is Money]]|date=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBupa's former Irish subsidiary, [[Bupa Ireland]], was set up in 1996 and eventually had three hundred employees in [[Fermoy]], [[County Cork]] and 475,000 members &ndash; a 22% share of the Irish market. In 2006 it announced its intention to close in response to the [[Irish Government]]'s policy of [[risk equalisation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BUPA to withdraw from Irish market |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2006/1214/bupa.html |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] |date=14 December 2006 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> In 2007 the business was bought by the [[Quinn Group]] and traded as [[Quinn Healthcare]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinn-group.com/divisions/divisions.cfm/display/maps/show/healthcare/quinn_healthcare.htm|title=Aventas Group - Welcome to Aventas Group|author=MJ Flood Technology|work=quinn-group.com|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> Since 2012 it has been trading as [[Laya Healthcare]], and since 2015 it has been owned by [[American International Group|AIG]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our story, our people |url=http://www.layahealthcare.ie/our_story.htm |publisher=Laya Healthcare Ireland |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2019, Bupa Australia was accused of not paying up on 270 invoices worth an estimated $73,000 to psychologists treating military personnel.The psychologist said there were bottlenecks with Bupa's referral system causing delays in appointment allocations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/14/bupa-defence-health-contract-warning-lives-could-be-at-risk-over-referrals-logjam|title=Bupa defence health contract: warning lives could be at risk over referrals logjam|last=Martin|first=Lisa|date=2019-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Bupa Australia admitted it had rejected 7,740 claims without a doctor's review in the five years before that date.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bupa apologises to customers for incorrect process |url=https://media.bupa.com.au/bupa-apologises-to-customers-for-incorrect-process/ |publisher=Bupa Australia |date=12 September 2016 |access-date=19 December 2019 |language=en-AU}}</ref> For years, it had falsely told customers that their rejections had been \"determined by a medical practitioner\". Bupa detected the failings itself and conducted its own internal investigation before referring the matter to the Department of Health. But the [[Ombudsmen in Australia#Commonwealth Ombudsman|Commonwealth Ombudsman]] had raised concerns about Bupa's compliance with the law two years earlier, in 2014. There was no public investigation to uncover the full extent of Bupa's failings.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Knaus |first=Christopher |date=8 July 2019 |title=Australia's biggest private health insurers illegally rejected thousands of claims |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/jul/08/australias-biggest-private-health-insurers-illegally-rejected-thousands-of-claims |work=The Guardian |access-date=19 December 2019 |language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nLeft an Australian elderly cancer patient with maggots 'crawling out of his ears' in 2017.  <ref>https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/maggots-crawling-out-ears-family-3280810 </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Bupa}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Major insurance companies}}\n\n[[Category:Health care companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Private companies limited by guarantee of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Dentistry in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Private providers of NHS services]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = Bupa\n| logo     = Bupa logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type     = [[Company limited by guarantee]]\n| location         = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|1947}}\n| key_people       = [[Evelyn Bourke]], CEO<br>Roger Davis, Chairman\n| industry         = [[Healthcare]], [[Insurance]]\n| products         = [[health insurance]], care homes, health at work services, hospitals, dental clinics, health assessments\n| revenue          = {{profit}} \u00a311.9 billion [[Pound sterling|GBP]] (2018)\n| operating_income = {{profit}} \u00a3613 million [[Pound sterling|GBP]] (2018)\n| num_employees    = 80,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{url|http://www.bupa.com}}\n}}\n'''Bupa''' {{IPAc-en|b|u\u02d0|p|\u0259}} is a British international [[healthcare]] provisioning and multi-[[insurance]] group, with its origins and headquarters in the United Kingdom, but now serving 32 million customers in 190 countries. It is a private healthcare [[company limited by guarantee]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Financial results |url=https://www.bupa.com/corporate/our-performance/financial-results |website=Bupa |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref> unlike the UK's [[National Health Service]] (NHS), which is a [[tax-funded healthcare]] system. While initially growing organically through [[Greenfield project|green-field]] expansions, it has recently tended to function akin to a [[Private Equity]] firm, with its corporate strategy heavily influenced by [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] activity in order to consolidate itself as a market leader in healthcare provisioning and multi-insurance. It is consistently ranked among the best places to work, having placed 5th in the 2019 edition of [[LinkedIn]]'s Top Companies in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carroll |first=Katie |date=3 April 2019 |title=Top Companies 2019: Where the UK wants to work now |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/top-companies-2019-where-uk-wants-work-now-katie-carroll/ |website=LinkedIn |accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nBupa (originally the '''British United Provident Association''') was established in 1947<ref name=\"Health Dialog sold 2007\"/> when seventeen British [[provident association]]s joined together to provide healthcare for the general public. The firm is a [[private company limited by guarantee]]; it has no [[shareholder]]s, and any [[profit (accounting)|profit]]s (after [[tax]]) are reinvested in the business. The service offered by Bupa began as private medical insurance, offering policies to individuals, companies and other organisations, and eventually expanded to include privately run Bupa hospitals.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n===Acquisitions and Divestments===\n\nIn 2007, the company announced the sale of its UK hospitals to [[Spire Healthcare]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kollewe |first=Julia |date=18 June 2007 |title=BUPA sells hospitals to private equity firm |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2007/jun/18/privateequity1 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> However, during 2008, the firm acquired the [[London]]-based [[Cromwell Hospital]] flagship hospital to provide healthcare to its members and other private patients including [[medical tourism|medical tourists]] from outside the UK.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nApproval was given in the same year for a merger between Bupa's Australian arm (which until then comprised HBA and Mutual Community) and insurance group MBF.<ref>{{cite web |title=MBF-BUPA merger gets court go ahead |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/05/14/2244271.htm |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)]] |date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=14 May 2008}}</ref> The merger created what is now Australia's largest private health insurance group, with 3.98m lives covered. On 1 December 2008, Clinovia's name was changed to '''Bupa Home Healthcare'''.  In October 2010 the firm sold Bupa Health Assurance to [[Resolution Limited]], and it has been rebranded as part of Friends Life.<ref>[http://www.ftadviser.com/FinancialAdviser/Insurance/HealthcareAndProtection/News/article/20101021/fcd4bb60-d849-11df-a180-00144f2af8e8/Bupa-insurance-operation-snapped-up-by-Resolution.jsp Bupa insurance operation snapped up by Resolution] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101024215648/http://www.ftadviser.com/FinancialAdviser/Insurance/HealthcareAndProtection/News/article/20101021/fcd4bb60-d849-11df-a180-00144f2af8e8/Bupa-insurance-operation-snapped-up-by-Resolution.jsp |date=24 October 2010 }} - Financial Times</ref> At the end of 2012 Bupa acquired the largest private healthcare network in [[Poland]], Lux Med, from the [[private equity]] fund [[Mid Europa Partners]] for \u20ac400m.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mid Europa Completes the Sale of LUX MED to Bupa |url=http://www.mideuropa.com/media/news/2013/mid-europa-completes-the-sale-of-lux-med-to-bupa/ |publisher=Mid Europa Partners |date=15 April 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> In February 2015 Bupa acquired a controlling share in Chilean private healthcare network Cruz Blanca, which has a 21% share in the local market.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grupo ingl\u00e9s Bupa Sanitas negocia compra de Cruz Blanca y pagar\u00e1 alto premio por acci\u00f3n |trans-title=English group Bupa Sanitas negotiates purchase of Cruz Blanca and will pay high premium per share |url=http://www.lasegunda.com/Noticias/Economia/2013/12/897015/grupo-ingles-negocia-compra-de-cruz-blanca-y-pagara-alto-premio-por-accion |newspaper=[[La Segunda]] |language=Spanish |date=2 December 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> It emerged in January 2016 that the company was to sell its domiciliary care business, which provided care to around 35,500 people, to [[Celesio]] AG.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celesio in exclusivity to acquire Bupa\u2019s home care division|url=http://healthinvestor.co.uk/ShowArticle.aspx?ID=4582|accessdate=27 January 2016|publisher=Health Investor|date=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOver the years, it has diversified away from its core health insurance business and is now an international healthcare company with services that include [[travel insurance]], [[health insurance]], [[care home]]s, [[expatriate insurance]], [[health assessments]], [[occupational health]] services and hospitals. When the [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]] came into force in April 2013 Bupa won the first high-value contract \u2013 a \u00a3235m deal to provide musculoskeletal services in West Sussex jointly with [[Central Surrey Health]] in November 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Denis |date=19 November 2014 |title=Private firms on course to net \u00a39bn of NHS contracts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/nov/19/private-firms-nhs-contracts-circle-healthcare-bupa-virgin-care-care-uk |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt bought the dentistry chain Oasis in November 2016 for \u00a3835 million from [[private equity]] firm [[Bridgepoint Capital]].  Oasis runs 380 UK dental practices, both NHS and private, with more than 1,800 dentists. It has an annual revenue of \u00a3277 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bupa snaps up dentistry group Oasis for \u00a3835m from private equity house Bridgepoint|url=http://www.cityam.com/253915/bupa-snaps-up-dentistry-group-oasis-835m-private-equity|accessdate=15 December 2016|newspaper=[[City AM]]|date=18 November 2016}}</ref> The name of the business was changed to Bupa Dental Care. In January 2019 it acquired 9 more practices, making a total of 23 in 6 months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bupa acquires nine new UK and Ireland dental practices |url=https://www.dentistry.co.uk/2019/01/23/bupa-acquires-nine-new-uk-ireland-dental-practices/ |accessdate=28 February 2019 |publisher=Dentistry |date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt bought two care homes in [[Poole]] from Primetower in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bupa UK acquires The Links and The Lindsay care homes in Poole|url=http://www.primetower.com/care.htm|accessdate=24 December 2016|publisher=Primetower}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017 it sold 122 care homes, with 9,000 beds, to [[HC-One]] for \u00a3300 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bow |first=Michael |date=23 August 2017 |title=HC-One seals Bupa \u00a3300m care home deal despite frets on debt |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/hcone-seals-bupa-300m-care-home-deal-despite-frets-on-debt-a3618196.html |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2018-19 financial year, Bupa remained the biggest player by customer numbers, with almost 3.6 million customers. However, the insurer has experienced losses in Australia- 50,000 net customer losses across all products and almost 80,000 of its core hospital cover customers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/companies/financial-services/bupa-biggest-loser-in-private-health-exodus-20191105-p537l3|title=Bupa biggest loser in private health exodus|last=Fernyhough|first=James|date=2019-11-05|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nThe company has its head office in central [[London]], with main UK contact centres in [[Staines]] and [[Salford Quays]]. There are also offices in [[Brighton]] (Bupa Global), [[Bristol]] (Bupa Dental Care) and [[Leeds]] (Bupa Care Services) in the UK, [[Adelaide]], [[Brisbane]], [[Sydney]] and [[Melbourne]] in Australia (Bupa Australia and Bupa Aged Care Australia), Chile (Bupa Chile), New Delhi (Max Bupa), Madrid (Sanitas), Boston ([[Health Dialog]]), Beijing (Bupa China), Hong Kong (Bupa Hong Kong & Quality Healthcare), Jeddah ([[Bupa Arabia]]), and Miami,{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n[[File:Sede de Sanitas (Madrid) 02.jpg|240px|thumbnail|Bupa (''Sanitas'') offices in [[Madrid]] ([[Spain]]).]]\nThe firm also owns several healthcare companies overseas including Spain's largest healthcare company, Sanitas, and acquired ihi Danmark and Amedex (Miami, US) in September 2005. In December 2007, it purchased DCA Agedcare Group in Australia and New Zealand, making it a leading player in these markets. Also in December 2007, it announced the purchase of [[Health Dialog]],<ref name=\"Health Dialog sold 2007\">{{cite web |title=Health Dialog sold in $775M deal |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/boston/stories/2007/12/17/daily26.html?jst=b_ln_hl |work=[[Boston Business Journal]] |date=18 December 2007 |accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> a provider of chronic condition management and \"shared decision making\" services.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nIn April 2013, the company acquired Lux Med, Poland's largest private healthcare provider which runs businesses in health funding and provision all over the country through a national network of 194 health centres, including outpatient facilities, diagnostic centres, hospitals, and a large nursing and residential care home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bupa.com/corporate/bupa-where-you-are/poland|title=Bupa in Poland|last=bupa.com|first=Bupa Corporate Website|date=17 July 2017|website=Bupa Corporate Website}}</ref>\n\nThe firm has entered the Indian health insurance market through a joint venture with the local conglomerate, [[Max Healthcare|Max India]], called '''[[Max Bupa]] Health Insurance Limited'''.<ref>[http://www.maxindia.com/newsjuly11.html Max India Press Release New Delhi, 11 July 2008.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510133025/http://www.maxindia.com/newsjuly11.html |date=10 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn the Middle East, Bupa has entered into a joint-venture partnership with Nazer Group \u2013 a family-owned diversified holding company \u2013 and created '''Bupa Middle East''' in 1997, operating out of [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abc-bahrain.com/companies/2841/bupa-middle-east-ltd | title=Bupa Middle East Ltd | publisher=Northstar Media | work=Arabian Business Community (ABC) | accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> When health insurance regulation issues arose in Saudi Arabia, the company was floated on the Saudi stock market as '''Bupa Arabia''', which is currently the leading health insurance company in Saudi Arabia.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nAccording to Stuart Fletcher in 2013 'there was a six percent decline in the number of individuals covered' by private health insurance, 'and the people who are more likely to claim are the least likely to drop the insurance, so the risk pool is deteriorating.' Bupa has protected its finances by reducing payments to consultants. This provoked the [[British Medical Association]] to complain to the [[Competition Commission]], which published a report into the private healthcare sector in 2013, probing insurers' power over consultants' fees. It decided that by trying to keep prices down and promote competition, Bupa was doing \"exactly what customers would expect\". But it did warn that companies like Bupa need to ensure they communicate better with policyholders about what their premiums entitle them to.<ref>{{cite news|title=CITY INTERVIEW: Boss Stuart Fletcher fighting the flab at Bupa|url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-2532338/CITY-INTERVIEW-Boss-Stuart-Fletcher-fighting-flab-Bupa.html|accessdate=3 January 2014 |author=Sunderland, Ruth |newspaper=[[This is Money]]|date=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBupa's former Irish subsidiary, [[Bupa Ireland]], was set up in 1996 and eventually had three hundred employees in [[Fermoy]], [[County Cork]] and 475,000 members &ndash; a 22% share of the Irish market. In 2006 it announced its intention to close in response to the [[Irish Government]]'s policy of [[risk equalisation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BUPA to withdraw from Irish market |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2006/1214/bupa.html |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] |date=14 December 2006 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> In 2007 the business was bought by the [[Quinn Group]] and traded as [[Quinn Healthcare]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quinn-group.com/divisions/divisions.cfm/display/maps/show/healthcare/quinn_healthcare.htm|title=Aventas Group - Welcome to Aventas Group|author=MJ Flood Technology|work=quinn-group.com|accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> Since 2012 it has been trading as [[Laya Healthcare]], and since 2015 it has been owned by [[American International Group|AIG]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our story, our people |url=http://www.layahealthcare.ie/our_story.htm |publisher=Laya Healthcare Ireland |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2019, Bupa Australia was accused of not paying up on 270 invoices worth an estimated $73,000 to psychologists treating military personnel.The psychologist said there were bottlenecks with Bupa's referral system causing delays in appointment allocations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/sep/14/bupa-defence-health-contract-warning-lives-could-be-at-risk-over-referrals-logjam|title=Bupa defence health contract: warning lives could be at risk over referrals logjam|last=Martin|first=Lisa|date=2019-09-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-10|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Bupa Australia admitted it had rejected 7,740 claims without a doctor's review in the five years before that date.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bupa apologises to customers for incorrect process |url=https://media.bupa.com.au/bupa-apologises-to-customers-for-incorrect-process/ |publisher=Bupa Australia |date=12 September 2016 |access-date=19 December 2019 |language=en-AU}}</ref> For years, it had falsely told customers that their rejections had been \"determined by a medical practitioner\". Bupa detected the failings itself and conducted its own internal investigation before referring the matter to the Department of Health. But the [[Ombudsmen in Australia#Commonwealth Ombudsman|Commonwealth Ombudsman]] had raised concerns about Bupa's compliance with the law two years earlier, in 2014. There was no public investigation to uncover the full extent of Bupa's failings.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Knaus |first=Christopher |date=8 July 2019 |title=Australia's biggest private health insurers illegally rejected thousands of claims |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/jul/08/australias-biggest-private-health-insurers-illegally-rejected-thousands-of-claims |work=The Guardian |access-date=19 December 2019 |language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nLeft an Australian elderly cancer patient with maggots 'crawling of of his ears' in 2017.  <ref>https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/maggots-crawling-out-ears-family-3280810 </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Bupa}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Major insurance companies}}\n\n[[Category:Health care companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the City of London]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Health care companies established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Private companies limited by guarantee of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1947 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Dentistry in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Private providers of NHS services]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bupa"}
